@stcheng  As the first step of eliminating global variables from Orch class, the change looks good to me.   
We should come up the new design asap.  With "gPortsOrch->isInitDone()" check in more places, 
it is a little like the spread of germs.

@xinliu-seattle @lguohan 
Have you added to the existing test framework for ACLs, test cases for this enhancement?
If so, can you point to the review of those test cases?

In previous code, 

```
        task_process_status task_status = ResolveMapAndApplyToPort(port, SAI_PORT_ATTR_QOS_DSCP_TO_TC_MAP, dscp_to_tc_field_name, tuple, op);
        if(task_process_status::task_failed == task_status)
        {
            return task_status;
        }
        task_status = ResolveMapAndApplyToPort(port, SAI_PORT_ATTR_QOS_TC_TO_QUEUE_MAP, tc_to_queue_field_name, tuple, op);
        if(task_process_status::task_failed == task_status)
        {
            return task_status;
        }
        task_status = ResolveMapAndApplyToPort(port, SAI_PORT_ATTR_QOS_TC_TO_PRIORITY_GROUP_MAP, tc_to_pg_map_field_name, tuple, op);
        if(task_process_status::task_failed == task_status)
        {
            return task_status;
        }
        task_status = ResolveMapAndApplyToPort(port, SAI_PORT_ATTR_QOS_PFC_PRIORITY_TO_PRIORITY_GROUP_MAP, pfc_to_pg_map_name, tuple, op);
        if(task_process_status::task_failed == task_status)
        {
            return task_status;
        }
        task_status = ResolveMapAndApplyToPort(port, SAI_PORT_ATTR_QOS_PFC_PRIORITY_TO_QUEUE_MAP, pfc_to_queue_map_name, tuple, op);
        if(task_process_status::task_failed == task_status)
        {
            return task_status;
        }
```

It only checks if the task is failed or not. It misses the possibility that the task needs retry. Thus, when the task needs retry, it is skipped instead of being applied. This leads to the lack of configurations.
